label.value: positive regulation of cellular response to alcohol

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cellular response to alcohol.

The area in the center of the anaphase spindle consisting of microtubules, microtubule bundling factors and kinesin motors where the spindle microtubules from opposite poles overlap in an antiparallel manner.

label.value: calcium ion export across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of calcium ions from inside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the extracellular region.
Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which glycerol is converted into glycerone and NAD+ or NADP is reduced.
Catalysis of the endonucleolytic cleavage immediately 5' to pyrimidine dimers to products with 5'-phosphate.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a messenger RNA (mRNA) molecule, initiated by the enzymatic addition of a sequence of uridylyl residues (polyuridylation) at the 3' end of the target mRNA.
A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within the nuclear periphery.
A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location at the cell tip.

label.value: maintenance of protein localization to heterochromatin

value.value: A process in which a protein is maintained in a location in telomeric heterochromatin.

label.value: Dsc E3 ubiquitin ligase complex assembly

value.value: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a Dsc E3 ubiquitin ligase complex, an E3 ubiquitin ligase complex localized to the ER and Golgi membrane.

label.value: protein localization to site of double-strand break

value.value: Any process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained at, a region of a chromosome at which a DNA double-strand break has occurred.
A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within the nucleoplasm.

label.value: protein localization to actomyosin contractile ring

value.value: A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained at, the actomyosin contractile ring.
The process in which the 3' end of a pre-tRNA molecule is converted to that of a mature tRNA in the mitochondrion.
Catalysis of the reaction: acetyl-CoA + N-terminal L-serine in peptide = CoA + N-acetyl-L-serine-peptide.
Catalysis of the reaction: acetyl-CoA + N-terminal L-glutamate in peptide = CoA + N-acetyl-L-glutamate-peptide.
Any protein complex that possesses oxidoreductase activity.

A protein complex capable of catalyzing the transfer of a group, e.g. a methyl group, glycosyl group, acyl group, phosphorus-containing, or other groups, from one compound (generally regarded as the donor) to another compound (generally regarded as the acceptor).
An nuclear body involved in nuclear mRNA surveilllance. Contains at least Mmi1, or an ortholog of it, and the nuclear exosome.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of deprivation of leucine.
Any disaggregation of an actomyosin contractile ring into its constituent components that is involved in a mitotic cell cycle.
A process in which RNA is transported to and maintained in a part of a chromosome that is organized into chromatin.

A cytoskeletal part that consists of an array of microtubules and associated molecules that forms at the end of anaphase, and in which microtubules are nucleated from an equatorial microtubule organizing center.

definition.value: The best-characterized example is found in the fission yeast Schizosaccharomyces pombe. The eMTOC is cortical, but the post-anaphase array microtubules are not exclusively cortical.

value.value: Protein complex that associates with the kinetochores.
A region of facultative heterochromatin formed dynamically at specific loci in response to environmental signals, independently of RNAi.

definition.value: An example of this type of heterochromatin is found in Schizosaccharomyces pombe, where heterochromatin islands are formed at meiotic genes during vegetative (mitotic) growth.

value.value: A region of heterochromatin that is formed dynamically under specific growth conditions by a process that requires RNAi, and is enriched in histone H3 methylated on lysine 9 (H3K9me).

definition.value: An example of this type of heterochromatin is found in Schizosaccharomyces pombe, where heterochromatin domains preferentially assemble at sexual differentiation genes and retrotransposons.

value.value: A cellular process that results in the biosynthesis of constituent macromolecules, assembly, and arrangement of constituent parts of a secondary cell septum following nuclear division.
A protein complex facilitating transport of molecules (proteins, small molecules, nucleic acids) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells.

definition.value: An example of this is GTR1 in human (UniProt symbol P11166) in PMID:15449578 (inferred from direct assay).

value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a disturbance in organismal or cellular homeostasis caused by a zinc ion stimulus.
A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the meiotic spindle pole body.
The posttranscriptional addition of a methyl group to the 2' oxygen atom of a nucleotide residue in an snRNA molecule.
The posttranscriptional addition a methyl group to the 2'-oxygen atom of a nucleotide residue in an U6 snRNA molecule.

A protein complex that is anchored at the cortical face of the plasma membrane, and contains proteins involved in regulating cell cycle progression. In Schizosaccharomyces pombe, lateral cortical nodes are several megadaltons in size, and contain Slf1, which anchors the complex at the membrane, and the methyltransferase Skb1 in stoichiometric quantities, and may contain other proteins.

Protein complex formed by an RNA binding protein Red1, an RNA helicase Mtl1, Red5, Rmn1, Iss10/Pir1, and Ars2/Pir2. This complex is required for the recruitment of the nuclear exosome to Mmi1 nuclear focus. It is likely related to the human CBCN complex. This complex is also known as RNA silencing (NURS) complex.

label.value: regulation of cytoplasmic translation in response to stress

value.value: Modulation of the frequency, rate or extent of cytoplasmic translation as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress. The stress is usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation).
Any microtubule that is part of a mitotic spindle; anchored at one spindle pole.

label.value: mitotic DNA replication maintenance of fidelity

value.value: Any maintenance of fidelity that is involved in mitotic cell cycle DNA replication.
The process by which centromeres/kinetochores attach to and migrate along microtubules to become localized to clusters at the spindle pole body during a meiotic prometaphase I.

label.value: potassium ion import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of potassium ions from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

Any of the meiotic spindle microtubules that radiate in all directions from the spindle poles and are thought to contribute to the forces that separate the poles and position them in relation to the rest of the cell.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of ester linkages within 3' overhang single-stranded deoxyribonucleic acid by creating internal breaks.
A process in which a mitotic spindle pole body is transported to, or maintained in, a specific cellular location.

label.value: regulation of cytoplasmic translational initiation in response to stress

value.value: Modulation of the frequency, rate or extent of cytoplasmic translational initiation as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress. The stress is usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation).

label.value: negative regulation of cytoplasmic translational initiation in response to stress

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate of cytoplasmic translation initiation as a result of a stimulus indicating the organism is under stress.
Any process that results in the specification, formation or maintenance of the physical structure of nucleolar chromatin.

label.value: astral microtubule anchoring at mitotic spindle pole body

value.value: Any process in which an astral microtubule is maintained in a specific location in a cell by attachment to a mitotic spindle pole body. Microtubules attach to spindle pole bodies at the minus end.

label.value: gamma-tubulin complex localization to mitotic spindle pole body

value.value: Any process in which a gamma-tubulin complex is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location at a mitotic spindle pole body.

Any process carried out at the cellular level that reduces or removes the toxicity of a toxic substance. These may include transport of the toxic substance away from sensitive areas and to compartments or complexes whose purpose is sequestration of the toxic substance.
The removal of tubulin heterodimers from one or both ends of a microtubule that is part of the mitotic spindle.

The mitotic cell cycle process in which sister chromatids establish stable, end-on attachments to the plus ends of microtubules emanating from opposite spindle poles, oriented such that separation can proceed. This is the final step in metaphase plate congression.
